<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section xml:id="sec-lawlargenumbers" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>The law of large numbers</title>
    <p>
        In the previous section, we introduced the distinction between <em>population parameters</em> and <em>sample statistics</em>. 
        Because sample statistics are calculated from only a subset of the population, they are unlikely to be exactly equal to the corresponding population parameters. 
        This raises an important question: how can we obtain more accurate estimates of the population?
    </p>

    <p>
        One of the simplest ways to improve the accuracy of statistical estimates is to increase the sample size. 
        As more observations are collected, the sample becomes more representative of the population, and sample statistics such as the sample mean and 
        sample standard deviation tend to move closer to their true population values.
    </p>

    <p>
        This principle is known as the <em>law of large numbers</em>. It states that as the sample size increases, 
        sample statistics based on averages become increasingly close to the corresponding population parameters. 
        For the sample mean, this means that as the sample size approaches infinity (<m>N \rightarrow \infty</m>), 
        the sample mean (<m>\bar{X}</m>) approaches the population mean (<m>\mu</m>).
    </p>

    <p>
        The law of large numbers provides the theoretical justification for collecting larger samples whenever possible. 
        Although any individual sample may differ from the population, 
        larger samples generally produce more reliable estimates because they reduce the effect of random sampling variation.
    </p>

    <p>
        The law applies not only to the sample mean but also to many other statistics that are based on averages. 
        It forms one of the fundamental principles of statistical inference and provides the basis for many of the estimation methods introduced later in this chapter.
    </p>
</section>